data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | ThreadAbortException as control flow |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | ResetAbort to continue execution |

## Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so your rollback logic **silently disappears**. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — mirrors the old ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed: we just continue to the while-condition
                // which will exit the loop since the token is cancelled.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();  // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish cleanly
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of preemptive kill |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids swallowing unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | Loop condition `!token.IsCancellationRequested` handles exit naturally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of hoping |
| *(nothing)* | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed to avoid timer/callback leaks |

## Critical pitfall: the blocking `GetNextItem()`

Your original `GetNextItem()` **may block indefinitely**. With the old code, `Thread.Abort()` would force-interrupt it. With cooperative cancellation, **it must accept and respect a token**:

```csharp
// If it wraps a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}

// If it wraps a synchronous wait (e.g., ManualResetEvent):
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it wraps Thread.Sleep:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollIntervalMs); // wakes on cancel
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return TryDequeue();
}
```

**If `GetNextItem` calls unmodifiable code that blocks forever**, you cannot cancel it cooperatively. In that case, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only safe equivalent to the old `Thread.Abort` for uncooperative code.

## Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` remains
- ✅ No `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks remain
- ✅ No `Thread.ResetAbort` calls remain
- ✅ Rollback logic preserved in `OperationCanceledException` handler
- ✅ `finally` / `FlushBuffers()` still runs
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed
- ✅ Token passed through to blocking calls
